   A federal appeals court in New York has allowed an ailing
railroad to sue Conrail for allegedly setting monopolistic
freight rates.
   The U.S. Second Circuit Court of Appeals overturned a
lower court decision dismissing the case. Delaware &amp; Hudson
Railway Co., which is in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings,
sued Conrail in 1986 over alleged antitrust violations in
Conrail's rate-setting policy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Delaware &amp; Hudson had to rely on part of the Conrail
system when it shipped newsprint from Canada to the middle
Atlantic states. In its suit, the company alleges that a
change in Conrail's rates in the early 1980s forced it out of
that market.
   The appeals court in Manhattan ruled that the lower-court
judge failed to adequately consider Conrail's monopolistic
power. The court said Delaware &amp; Hudson either had to give up
its business in the market or pay a sharp increase to Conrail
that would wipe out its profits on the middle Atlantic route.
   Delaware &amp; Hudson, one of Conrail's few rail-freight
competitors in the Northeast, filed for Chapter 11 protection
in 1988. James K. Manning, an attorney for Delaware &amp; Hudson,
said the change in Conrail's rate-setting policy contributed
to the railroad's financial troubles. "In our view, this has
been part of the problem," said Mr. Manning. "We were denied
any economic access in this market." For Delaware &amp; Hudson,
the newsprint market was "quite important because it happens
to be a market that was well-suited to rail traffic," Mr.
Manning said.
   Attorneys for Conrail, a private rail freight company set
up by Congress in 1976, couldn't be reached for comment.
   Conrail, based in Philadelphia, had claimed in the
district court that its practices weren't anti-competitive
because it was merely trying to maximize its profits. The
appeals court, however, said that considering Conrail's
control over the market, there are grounds for a trial to
determine whether the rate policy was monopolistic. Delaware
&amp; Hudson is seeking damages of more than $5 million, which
would be trebled under antitrust law.
