   SOVIET SANCTIONS in Lithuania jeopardize opportunities for
U.S. lawyers.
   American law firms promoting joint ventures in the Soviet
Union are concluding that now is not the time to move into
the Baltic republics. James Dobkin, who leads Arnold &amp;
Porter's international joint venture practice, says that his
clients who had considered such projects have decided that
they are unthinkable now, "at least for the immediate
future."
   Ed Lieberman, a partner at the Washington-based firm of
Cole Corette &amp; Abrutyn, agrees that American law firms and
their clients are staying away from the Baltics "as a result
of concerns about Lithuania."
   Tensions in Lithuania are having less effect on American
legal entrepreneurship elsewhere in the Soviet Union. But Mr.
Lieberman worries that rising tensions in Lithuania could
scuttle trade and tax treaties being readied for discussion
at the May summit, which in turn could slow the efforts of
American law firms trying to develop a Soviet market for
their clients.
   Assistant U.S. trade representative Peter Allegeier told
lawyers and businessmen last week that the U.S. is assuming
that events in Lithuania won't disrupt trade.
