   ATTORNEY GENERAL pessimistic about recouping losses from
S&amp;L fraud.
   "I don't think a lot of this money is available," said
U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, after a speech
yesterday in Dallas. Recovery is complicated, he said,
because "some of those assets have been dissipated," and some
of the top suspects have sought bankruptcy-court protection.
   But the U.S. Justice Department is making an effort to
obtain restitution in certain instances. In Dallas last week,
Justice Department prosecutor Robert Hauberg urged a federal
judge to order Woody F. Lemons, former chief executive
officer of defunct Vernon Savings &amp; Loan Association of
Dallas, to turn over $9.7 million to the government. U.S.
District Judge Robert B. Maloney hasn't ruled on the
restitution request but he isn't expected to treat the
prosecutor's motion lightly.
   Earlier this month, the judge sentenced Mr. Lemons to 30
years in federal prison, one of the stiffest terms to date in
a thrift-related fraud case.
